Frequently Asked Questions (FAQs)
Q: What are the general admission requirements for UK universities?

A: Admission requirements vary depending on the course and university. Generally, you need a high school diploma or equivalent, proof of English proficiency (e.g., IELTS or TOEFL), and, for some programs, standardized test scores (e.g., SAT or ACT). It's advisable to check specific requirements with Qadri-international.

Q: How much does it cost to study in UK?

A: Tuition fees in the UK vary by university and course. On average, international undergraduate students can expect to pay between £10,000 and £38,000 per year. Additionally, living costs range from £9,000 to £12,000 per year, depending on the location. Scholarships and financial aid are available to help offset these costs.

Q: Can I work while studying in the UK?

A: Yes, international students on a Tier 4 student visa can work up to 20 hours per week during term time and full-time during holidays. This allows students to gain work experience and support themselves financially.

Q: How do I apply for a UK student visa?

A: After receiving an unconditional offer from a UK university, you can apply for a Tier 4 (General) student visa. You'll need a Confirmation of Acceptance for Studies (CAS) from your university, proof of financial means, and other supporting documents. Qadri-international can assist you with the visa application process.
